<DOC><DOCNO> AP880629-0288 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0150EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   06-29 0574</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0600</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Securities pros say the latest insider tradingscheme alleged by the government against a Morgan Stanley andamp; Co.analyst and a client raises big questions about whether Wall Streethas been properly policing itself in the aftermath of the IvanBoesky scandal.   Securities lawyers and professionals say they are shocked thatMorgan trainee Stephen Wang Jr. could have obtained access tosecrets about corporate takeovers and systematically misused them.   Washington attorney Paul Fischer said Tuesday that the scheme``seems to suggest that even the real threat of criminalprosecution and jail sentences isn't enough to eradicate insidertrading.''</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Wall Street felon Ivan F. Boesky, center of amassive insider trading scandal, has been transferred from a U.S.prison in California to a detention facility in New York, federalprison officials said.   The move immediately raised speculation that he would testifyagainst others implicated in the scandal, although officials saidthey didn't know the exact reason for the temporary transfer.   Boesky was moved from a minimum-security prison camp in Lompoc,Calif., to the Metropolitan Correctional Facility in Manhattan June23, said Joseph Fitzmaurice, a Lompoc correctional officer reachedby telephone.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The suffocating drought in mid-America is taking its toll onscores of smaller crops _ from cherries to honey _ that couldresult in huge losses for thousands of growers.   Although the spotlight about the drought's impact has focused onthe enormous grain and livestock industries, analysts say thedrought will affect just about everything grown from the RockyMountains east to Ohio.   The result could be a change in diets and higher prices atgrocery stores, restaurants and taverns.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Corn and soybean futures prices plummeted bytheir daily limits on the Chicago Board of Trade in a wild reversalbased on concerns that rain may fall across the Midwest and bringrelief to drought-stricken crops.   Victor Lespinasse, an analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.,said Tuesday that talk of rain ``caused massive liquidation'' amongbuyers in the corn and soybean pits who had been anticipating thedrought would continue to damage crops and tighten supplies.</TEXT><DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Farmers are putting off buying tractorsand delaying equipment repairs because of the drought, just as farmequipment manufacturers were beginning to enjoy a rebound from aneight-year slump.   Although some say it's too early to gauge the drought's impacton the industry, others say the uncertainty comes at a bad time.   George Dahlman, an analyst who follows the farm equipmentindustry for the Minneapolis securities firm of Piper Jaffrey andamp;Hopwood Inc., said Tuesday that the drought will mean a significantbackwards slide for farm equipment sales but won't pushmanufacturers into bankruptcy.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Federal officials have extended thenegotiating deadline for Texas billionaire Robert M. Bass in hiseffort to take over troubled American Savings and Loan Association,the nation's second largest thrift.   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which regulates the Sandamp;Lindustry, had announced on April 21 that it would negotiateexclusively with the Robert M. Bass Group for a period of 75 days,ending on July 5.   But the bank board said the ``complexity of the transaction''warranted the extension until Aug. 1. for the Stockton,Calif.-based American Savings, the main unit of Financial Corp. ofAmerica of Irvine, Calif.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>